==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hawser
<hw>Haws"er</hw> <pr>(h⟦add⟧z"⟦etil⟧r <it>or</it> h⟦add⟧s"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From F. <ets>hausser</ets> to lift, raise (cf. OF.
<ets>hausser⟦eacute⟧e</ets> towpath, towing, F.
<ets>haussi⟦egrave⟧re</ets> hawser), LL. <ets>altiare</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>altus</ets> high. See <er>Haughty</er>.]</ety> <def>A large rope
made of three strands each containing many yarns.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Three hawsers twisted together make a cable; but it
nautical usage the distinction between cable and hawser is often one of
size rather than of manufacture.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hawser iron</b></col>, <cd>a calking iron.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hawser-laid</ent>⟦br⟧
